title: Tengu Derby held in Elliott Bay since 1946 likely won’t happen this winter due to Central Sound closure
text:
Tengu Derby held in Elliott Bay since 1946 likely won’t happen this winter due to Central Sound closure Originally published October 16, 2015 at 9:54 pm Updated October 16, 2015 at 9:58 pm Anglers take to the water off Alki. Elliott Bay is the scene for the annual Tengu Derby. 
The summer-long hatchery chinook fishing closure in central Puget Sound was not a welcome sight for anglers, and after being open this month for a little more than two weeks it will be shutdown once again. 
State Fish and Wildlife has decided to close down the popular stretch of marine area after Sunday (Oct. 18) since the wild chinook encounter guideline was expected to be achieved. The area was supposed to remain open through Jan. 31. 
According to data, anglers had 1,512 chinook encounters through Oct. 11 under a guideline of 2,221. 
State fishery managers will crunch numbers to see if enough remains to possibly reopen the area at some point in the near future. Most Read Stories
